issue.title: Celery worker deletes task from MQ during fetching after shutdown
issue.body:
# Checklist - [x] I have verified that the issue exists against the `master` branch of Celery. - [ ] This has already been asked to the [discussions forum](https://github.com/celery/celery/discussions) first. - [x] I have read the relevant section in the [contribution guide](https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/master/contributing.html#other-bugs) on reporting bugs. - [x] I have checked the [issues list](https://github.com/celery/celery/issues?q=is%3Aissue+label%3A%22Issue+Type%3A+Bug+Report%22+-label%3A%22Category%3A+Documentation%22) for similar or identical bug reports. - [x] I have checked the [pull requests list](https://github.com/celery/celery/pulls?q=is%3Apr+label%3A%22PR+Type%3A+Bugfix%22+-label%3A%22Category%3A+Documentation%22) for existing proposed fixes. - [x] I have checked the [commit log](https://github.com/celery/celery/commits/master) to find out if the bug was already fixed in the master branch. - [x] I have included all related issues and possible duplicate issues in this issue (If there are none, check this box anyway). ## Mandatory Debugging Information - [x] I have included the output of ``celery -A proj report`` in the issue. (if you are not able to do this, then at least specify the Celery version affected). - [x] I have verified that the issue exists against the `master` branch of Celery. - [x] I have included the contents of ``pip freeze`` in the issue. - [x] I have included all the versions of all the external dependencies required to reproduce this bug. ## Optional Debugging Information - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one Python version and/or implementation. - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one message broker and/or result backend. - [x] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one version of the message broker and/or result backend. - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one operating system. - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one workers pool. - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue with autoscaling, retries, ETA/Countdown & rate limits disabled. - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue after downgrading and/or upgrading Celery and its dependencies. ## Related Issues and Possible Duplicates #### Related Issues - None #### Possible Duplicates - None ## Environment & Settings **Celery version**: 5.2.7 and 4.3.0
celery report Output:

``` software -> celery:5.2.7 (dawn-chorus) kombu:5.2.4 py:3.8.0 billiard:3.6.4.0 redis:4.4.0 platform -> system:Linux arch:64bit, ELF kernel version:5.15.0-56-generic imp:CPython loader -> celery.loaders.app.AppLoader settings -> transport:redis results:redis://:**@localhost:6379/ Queue: broker_url: 'redis://:********@localhost:6379//' imports: ('worker',) logging: result_backend: 'redis://:********@localhost:6379/' task_queues: [ -> >] task_routes: { 'task*': {'queue': 'test'}} worker_concurrency: 1 worker_prefetch_multiplier: 1 deprecated_settings: None ```

# Steps to Reproduce ## Required Dependencies * **Minimal Python Version**: 3.8 * **Minimal Celery Version**: 4.3.0 * **Minimal Kombu Version**: 4.6.11 * **Minimal Broker Version**: 7.0 * **Minimal Result Backend Version**: 7.0 * **Minimal OS and/or Kernel Version**: Ubuntu 22.04 and kernel version:5.15.0-56-generic * **Minimal Broker Client Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Result Backend Client Version**: N/A or Unknown ### Python Packages
pip freeze Output:

``` amqp==5.1.1 async-timeout==4.0.2 billiard==3.6.4.0 celery==5.2.7 click==8.1.3 click-didyoumean==0.3.0 click-plugins==1.1.1 click-repl==0.2.0 kombu==5.2.4 prompt-toolkit==3.0.36 psutil==5.9.4 pytz==2022.6 redis==4.4.0 six==1.16.0 vine==5.0.0 wcwidth==0.2.5 ```

### Other Dependencies

N/A

## Minimally Reproducible Test Case

celeryconfig.py ```python from kombu import Queue broker_url = "redis://password@localhost:6379" result_backend = "redis://:password@localhost:6379" imports = ("worker",) worker_concurrency = 1 worker_prefetch_multiplier = 1 task_routes = {'task*': {'queue': 'test'}} task_queues = [Queue("test")] ``` worker.pi ```python import logging import time from celery import Celery import celeryconfig app = Celery("test") app.config_from_object(celeryconfig) logger = logging.getLogger(__name__) @app.task(name="task1") def task1(): pass ``` main.py ```python import signal import subprocess import time import redis from worker import task1 if __name__ == '__main__': r = redis.Redis(host='localhost', port=6379, db=0, password="") while True: # You may need to edit the initial timeout, depending on how fast/slow your PC is timeout = 1.2439 # this value actual for my PC step = 0.00001 # we will increase timeout with such step to catch the error task_id = task1.delay().task_id while True: try: p = subprocess.Popen(["celery", "-A", "worker", "worker", "-l", "info", "-E"]) time.sleep(timeout) p.send_signal(signal.SIGINT) except (subprocess.TimeoutExpired, BrokenPipeError): pass print(timeout) # Checking if there are task still in our queue. We need to continue test, # if that's true if r.lrange("test", 0, 1): timeout += step else: break # Sometimes we may miss the timing, so if the task is processed, we start all over again is_task_processed = not r.get("celery-task-meta-" + task_id) if is_task_processed: break ```

# Expected Behavior The task will be fetched from the queue when a warm shutdown is received. Expected redis operations: ``` LPUSH test {"body": "W1tdLCB7fSwgeyJjYWxsYmFja3MiOiBudWxsLCAiZXJyYmFja3MiOiBudWxsLCAiY2hhaW4iOiBudWxsLCAiY2hvcmQiOiBudWxsfV0=", "content-encoding": "utf-8", "content-type": "application/json", "headers": {"lang": "py", "task": "task1", "id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "shadow": null, "eta": null, "expires": null, "group": null, "group_index": null, "retries": 0, "timelimit": [null, null], "root_id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "parent_id": null, "argsrepr": "()", "kwargsrepr": "{}", "origin": "gen13915@igor-pc-work", "ignore_result": false}, "properties": {"correlation_id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "reply_to": "36f586c8-1387-3a19-8eb3-12dbefcfaeb8", "delivery_mode": 2, "delivery_info": {"exchange": "", "routing_key": "test"}, "priority": 0, "body_encoding": "base64", "delivery_tag": "beeb3fc1-8524-4212-a14d-9bee5343f353"}} RPOP test MULTI ZADD unacked_index 1670591793.386102 beeb3fc1-8524-4212-a14d-9bee5343f353 HSET unacked beeb3fc1-8524-4212-a14d-9bee5343f353 [{"body": "W1tdLCB7fSwgeyJjYWxsYmFja3MiOiBudWxsLCAiZXJyYmFja3MiOiBudWxsLCAiY2hhaW4iOiBudWxsLCAiY2hvcmQiOiBudWxsfV0=", "content-encoding": "utf-8", "content-type": "application/json", "headers": {"lang": "py", "task": "task1", "id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "shadow": null, "eta": null, "expires": null, "group": null, "group_index": null, "retries": 0, "timelimit": [null, null], "root_id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "parent_id": null, "argsrepr": "()", "kwargsrepr": "{}", "origin": "gen13915@igor-pc-work", "ignore_result": false}, "properties": {"correlation_id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "reply_to": "36f586c8-1387-3a19-8eb3-12dbefcfaeb8", "delivery_mode": 2, "delivery_info": {"exchange": "", "routing_key": "test"}, "priority": 0, "body_encoding": "base64", "delivery_tag": "beeb3fc1-8524-4212-a14d-9bee5343f353"}}, "", "test"] EXEC ``` # Actual Behavior The task is removed from the custom queue and is not moved to the unacked queue When fetching a task from the queue, the worker calls the RPOP function in redis and moves the returned task to unacked. In my case, if you get to the right timing with the worker turned off, then the worker will only call RPOP in redis and then shutdown without transferring the task to unacked. Thus, the task will simply be deleted. Actual redis operations logs : ``` LPUSH test {"body": "W1tdLCB7fSwgeyJjYWxsYmFja3MiOiBudWxsLCAiZXJyYmFja3MiOiBudWxsLCAiY2hhaW4iOiBudWxsLCAiY2hvcmQiOiBudWxsfV0=", "content-encoding": "utf-8", "content-type": "application/json", "headers": {"lang": "py", "task": "task1", "id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "shadow": null, "eta": null, "expires": null, "group": null, "group_index": null, "retries": 0, "timelimit": [null, null], "root_id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "parent_id": null, "argsrepr": "()", "kwargsrepr": "{}", "origin": "gen13915@igor-pc-work", "ignore_result": false}, "properties": {"correlation_id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "reply_to": "36f586c8-1387-3a19-8eb3-12dbefcfaeb8", "delivery_mode": 2, "delivery_info": {"exchange": "", "routing_key": "test"}, "priority": 0, "body_encoding": "base64", "delivery_tag": "beeb3fc1-8524-4212-a14d-9bee5343f353"}} RPOP test ``` P.S. We have such a problem in a production using Kuber autoscaling in the Google cloud.

If you don't know how to mention issues, please refer to Github's documentation
on the subject: https://help.github.com/en/articles/autolinked-references-and-urls#issues-and-pull-requests
-->

#### Related Issues

- https://github.com/celery/celery/issues/6348
  - The situation is similar, but this issue is based on Redis Sentinel and we use AWS ElastiCache. Error message is also a bit different.

#### Possible Duplicates

- None

# Brief Summary
<!--
Please include a brief summary of what the enhancement is
and why it is needed.
-->

When AWS ElastiCache for Redis has a replication structure and causes a failover, Celery doesn't failover and the main process tries graceful shutdown. It means,
- main process exits due to Unrecoverable error when there is no remaining task
- main process hangs until the remaining task finishes

The second one is critical for us because we have many long ongoing tasks. The first one is better than it because we automatically reboot the process, but we'd like to avoid it because Redis failover is a kind of expected behavior.

If some change is acceptable, we will try to create a pull request by ourselves.

# Detail

We got the following error when ElastiCache failover happened.
```
[CRITICAL - 2022-11-04 10:45:27 - 21 worker:207] Unrecoverable error: ReadOnlyError("You can't write against a read only replica.")
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/celery/worker/worker.py", line 203, in start
    self.blueprint.start(self)
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/celery/bootsteps.py", line 116, in start
    step.start(parent)
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/celery/bootsteps.py", line 365, in start
    return self.obj.start()
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/celery/worker/consumer/consumer.py", line 326, in start
    blueprint.start(self)
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/celery/bootsteps.py", line 116, in start
    step.start(parent)
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/celery/worker/consumer/consumer.py", line 618, in start
    c.loop(*c.loop_args())
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/celery/worker/loops.py", line 97, in asynloop
    next(loop)
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/kombu/asynchronous/hub.py", line 362, in create_loop
    cb(*cbargs)
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/kombu/transport/redis.py", line 1266, in on_readable
    self.cycle.on_readable(fileno)
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/kombu/transport/redis.py", line 504, in on_readable
    chan.handlers[type]()
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/kombu/transport/redis.py", line 898, in _brpop_read
    **options)
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/redis/client.py", line 1189, in parse_response
    response = connection.read_response()
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/redis/connection.py", line 817, in read_response
    raise response
redis.exceptions.ReadOnlyError: You can't write against a read only replica.
```

As far as we checked, an error during connection becomes `ConnectionError` and regarded as "Recoverable", but `ReadOnlyError` (and its parent `ResponseError`) is regarded as "Unrecoverable".

# Design

## Architectural Considerations
<!--
If more components other than Celery are involved,
describe them here and the effect it would have on Celery.
-->
Maybe this part in kombu is related
https://github.com/celery/kombu/blob/v5.2.3/kombu/transport/redis.py#L128-L141

## Proposed Behavior
<!--
Please describe in detail how this enhancement is going to change the behavior
of an existing feature.
Describe what happens in case of failures as well if applicable.
-->
When an error happens due to switching master to replica, retry connection and connect to the new master.

## Proposed UI/UX
<!--
Please provide your ideas for the API, CLI options,
configuration key names etc. that will be adjusted for this enhancement.
-->
- Adding some option to regard ResponseError as "Recoverable".  Configuration key like `redis_retry_on_response_error` or `redis_retry_on_failover`?

But we're not sure if regarding ResponseError as "Recoverable" has a critical impact on existing behavior. We'd really appreciate advice from the community.

## Diagrams
<!--
Please include any diagrams that might be relevant
to the implementation of this enhancement such as:
* Class Diagrams
* Sequence Diagrams
* Activity Diagrams
You can drag and drop images into the text box to attach them to this issue.
-->

## Alternatives
<!--
If you have considered any alternative implementations
describe them in detail below.
-->

issue.title: ignore_result in task-decorator is ignored
issue.body:
Occurring in celery 5.2.7

When using celery with redis result-backend, passing `ignore_result` to the task decorator has no influence on the task result being stored.

```python3
@celery.task(ingore_result=True)
def task_2(*args, **kwargs):
    return "t2 return"

# these calls will create a celery-task-meta-<task_id> key in the corresponding redis result-backend
task_2.apply_async(ignore_result=False)
task_2.apply_async()
# this call will not store anything in the result backend
task_2.apply_async(ignore_result=True)
```

According to the [docs](https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/latest/userguide/tasks.html#ignore-results-you-don-t-want) the option precedence order is:

1.  Global [task_ignore_result](https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/latest/userguide/configuration.html#std-setting-task_ignore_result)
2.  [ignore_result](https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/latest/reference/celery.app.task.html#celery.app.task.Task.ignore_result) option
3.  Task execution option ignore_result

So i would expect `task_2.apply_async()` to ignore its result.

issue.title: Pulling the rug out from under FOSS users
issue.body:
I've used Rainbow Brackets for ages. The initial release was way good enough - just the paired-brackets support was great.

Since then, there's been a bunch of features added - of which I use none. However, I see now a change such that I need to pay for these features that I don't want - the plugin remains disabled unless I select to either pay, or go on a trial license, because I'm writing code in C#.

I understand the desire to make money off of your own software - and it's _your_ software to choose with what _you_ want to do - but I feel like the rug was pulled out from under existing users. The licensing info says that the free features remain free, but suddenly, C# isn't free. It's quite disappointing. The price, being in dollars, isn't (imo) a fair trade; neither is a recurring payment system for a user who has never, ever needed support - as I say, the initial offering was exactly what I was looking for.

issue.title: User Agents outdated
issue.body:
<!-- 🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅
Hi there! 😄

To expedite issue processing please search open and closed issues before submitting a new one. Existing issues often contain information about workarounds, resolution, or progress updates.
🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅 -->

# 🐞 bug report

### ✍️ Description

We use [browserslist-useragent-regexp](https://github.com/browserslist/browserslist-useragent-regexp) to check that our users are not using older browsers.
But your User Agents are outdated, especially for Iphone devices.
For example you define this: `Mozilla/5.0 (iPhone; CPU iPhone OS 13_2_3 like Mac OS X) AppleWebKit/605.1.15 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/13.0.3 Mobile/15E148 Safari/604.1` for the Iphone 12 Pro. However iOS 13 was released in September 2019. On iPhone, browsers are updated with the OS, so we consider this browser to be obsolete.
You should change `iPhone OS 13_2_3` to `iPhone OS 16_1`
This problem occurs on many User Agents, even desktop ones.

It seems to be the same issue as here [703](https://github.com/responsively-org/responsively-app/issues/703)

### 🔧 Hypothetical solutions

I see two solutions, either regularly update the hardcoded values or allow editing of the preconfigured devices.

### 🕵🏼‍♂️ Is this a regression?

No.

### 🔬 Minimal Reproduction

Just follow the 4 steps from [browserslist-useragent-regexp](https://github.com/browserslist/browserslist-useragent-regexp#browserslist-useragent-regexp)

You can test our [website](https://demo-sitecarriere-classique.cvcatcher.io/) in the app, and you will be redirected to the "unsupported browsers" page.

### 🔥 Screenshot

![Demo-sitecarriere-classique - Full - iPhone 12-13 Pro - 2022-12-01 at 11 07 43 AM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/38187278/205025812-19dbc65e-ab80-4fe7-8189-fc8fdc252b09.jpg)

issue.title: About task_acks_late
issue.body:
Hi all,
         After i  read the doc about the [task_acks_late](https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/stable/glossary.html#term-late-acknowledgment),  i do the test but found something not the same as description, my procedure was the following:

First start the celery worker in one shell and it will consume the default queue task
```
celery -A celery_ini worker -l info
```

Celery App configure like this:
```
from celery import Celery
app = Celery('tasks1', broker="redis://:xxxxx@xxxxx:xxxxx/0",
             backend="mongodb://xxxxx:xxxxx@xxxxx:xxxxx/xxxxx?authSource=xxxxx&maxPoolSize=xxxxx&replicaSet=xxxxx",
             include=["tasks"])
app.conf.update(
    worker_concurrency=2,
    worker_prefetch_multiplier=2,
    task_acks_late=True
)
```

Add task code like this:
```
@app.task
  def add(x, y):
      import time
      time.sleep(30)
      print(f"x+y={x+y}")
      return x + y
```

and i call the task in another shell 
```
from tasks import add
from celery import group
all_tasks=group(add.s(1,i) for i in range(6))
all_tasks.delay()
```

Now ,if as the prefork thread was doing the first 2 job we kill the worker use this cmd 
```
for i in `ps -ef | grep celery | grep -v grep | grep -v flower | awk '{print $2}'`;do kill -9 $i;done;
```   
 
i lost the **exec task** and **reserved task** , the broker was only have **2** task,

but the doc say this， 

> late acknowledgment
Task is [acknowledged](https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/stable/glossary.html#term-acknowledged) after execution (both if successful, or if the task is raising an error), which means the task will be redelivered to another worker in the event of the machine losing power, or the worker instance being killed mid-execution.

so was i misunderstanding this ? can anyone help me ?

issue.title: Statistics of Workers: Add information of idle state
issue.body:
# Checklist

- [x] I have checked the [issues list](https://github.com/celery/celery/issues?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=is%3Aissue+label%3A%22Issue+Type%3A+Feature+Request%22+)
  for similar or identical feature requests.
- [x] I have checked the [pull requests list](https://github.com/celery/celery/pulls?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=is%3Apr+label%3A%22PR+Type%3A+Feature%22+)
  for existing proposed implementations of this feature.
- [x] I have checked the [commit log](https://github.com/celery/celery/commits/master)
  to find out if the same feature was already implemented in the
  master branch.
- [x] I have included all related issues and possible duplicate issues
  in this issue (If there are none, check this box anyway).

## Related Issues and Possible Duplicates
- None

#### Related Issues

- None

#### Possible Duplicates

- None

# Brief Summary
I'd like to determine if a worker is idle (no new tasks available and non currently executed) and how long it is already in this state.

I'm running celery workers in a self-scaling environment.
Depending on this idle-state I'd like to automatically scale the amount of workers up or down by an external "auto-scaler".

This could be done by increase/decrease the `replicas` spec of the parent `Deployment`, adjusting `minReplicas` of an `HorizontalPodAutoscaler` of K8s or to start/stop pods using the K8s API.
For docker-compose one can use the `--scale` parameter etc - just to name a few possibilities.

[The scaling algorithm I'd like to implement is something like GitLab is using](https://docs.gitlab.com/runner/configuration/autoscale.html#autoscaling-algorithm-and-parameters).
It works by checking how many workers are idle (and how long) which results in scaling down if it exceeds a certain treshold or if all of them are busy, scaling up so that anytime X workers are free (and thus idle) to pick new tasks.

Celery provides `control.inspect().active()` which outputs the current running tasks per worker.
However, on very short-running tasks and `concurrent=1` and `prefetch=0` this nearly always returns an empty list.
Independent if this is a "good" celery configuration, because of this, it would not be a applicable way of getting the current state of a worker.

Celery provides a `control.inspect().stats()` command.
It includes a `total` dictionary with task names as keys and the amount of tasks executed by the worker as values.
One could sum up those values and keep track if they increase to determine if the worker "is still working".

# Design

## Architectural Considerations
None

## Proposed Behavior
Add additional information to the `stats()` command for each worker to determine how long a worker is idle.
That could be done by adding `idle` as an additional return value which consists of `int` seconds since the worker worked on a task.
For long running tasks this value stays at `0`.

External scripts could check this value to determine if a worker is idle - at least in Python it would automatically evaluate to `false` if `0` and is otherwise `true`.
Also it gives the developer the freedom to decide to wait until `idle` exceeds a given threshold before any action is taken.

## Proposed UI/UX
N/A _API/CLI only_

## Diagrams
N/A

## Alternatives
None (see summary)

issue.title: Disabling 'Semantic highlighting' should disable rainbow variables
issue.body:
## Expected Behavior
Disabling the default `Semantic highlighting` option should also disable the plugin `Enable rainbow variable` option.

## Current Behavior
Disabling the default `Semantic highlighting`  works for the current project, but the option gets activated back when you open a new project/restart the editor.

---

Got a notification suggesting to use rainbow variables, wanted to try it but didn't understood it was coming from this plugin because I had to activate an option in the default editor settings.
Didn't liked the way it looked so I tried to disabled it, but couldn't figure out why the editor couldn't keep the setting disabled.

Don't know if there is a good fix for that but other people might have the same issue.

Thx for the great work on the plugin !

## Related Issues and Possible Duplicates
<!--

If you don't know how to mention issues, please refer to Github's documentation
on the subject: https://help.github.com/en/articles/autolinked-references-and-urls#issues-and-pull-requests

#### Related Issues

- [Celery 7911](https://github.com/celery/celery/issues/7911)

#### Possible Duplicates

- None

# Brief Summary
<!--
Please include a brief summary of what the feature does
and why it is needed.
-->
Redis has a limit of 512MB for String values. While generating tasks, some may get larger than that limit resulting in a BackendStoreError https://github.com/celery/celery/issues/6533. In applications where a size larger than 512MB might be expected, we'd like to chunk the task down to manageable pieces and then coalesce the data when it's needed.

This is related to the other issue I posted, https://github.com/celery/celery/issues/7911, since we would be able to send the IDs of the chunked data and then merge the results later on when a worker has picked up the task.

Some brokers, in our case SQS, do not support large tasks (>256KB). Rather than send the task data through the broker, one may want to save the task data to the result backend, in our case specifically Redis, and only send an ID for that data through the broker allowing larger tasks to support more brokers.

There is an [issue](https://github.com/celery/kombu/issues/279) for kombu that seeks to fix the size limit for but if a result_backend is present, wouldn't it be better to save the task to that, and then load it when it's needed? While https://github.com/celery/kombu/issues/279 fixes SQS, it won't fix RabbitMQ's 512MB max limit, which we have also hit on some occasions. In cases when using a broker with a heavily limited size cap, like SQS, or when generating and sending incredibley large tasks, only sending a result_id referencing the result data stored in the backend would be helpful.

# Design

## Architectural Considerations
<!--
If more components other than Celery are involved,
describe them here and the effect it would have on Celery.
-->
None

## Proposed Behavior
<!--
Please describe in detail how this feature is going to behave.
Describe what happens in case of failures as well if applicable.
-->
* In the trace module https://github.com/celery/celery/blob/master/celery/app/trace.py#L448 before executing the celery task, the `result_backend_data` should be restored using the id in that dict, this key should be present in the kwargs 
* apply_async calls in https://github.com/celery/celery/blob/master/celery/app/trace.py#L479-L504 should be modified to only the id using result_backend_data, and not the actual result data

## Proposed UI/UX
<!--
Please provide your ideas for the API, CLI options,
configuration key names etc. that will be introduced for this feature.
-->

## Diagrams

issue.title: Use bound task in base task example
issue.body:
<!--

bug reports which are incomplete.
-->
# Checklist
<!--
To check an item on the list replace [ ] with [x].
-->

- [x] I have checked the [issues list](https://github.com/celery/celery/issues?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=is%3Aissue+label%3A%22Category%3A+Documentation%22+)
  for similar or identical bug reports.

  for existing proposed fixes.
- [x] I have checked the [commit log](https://github.com/celery/celery/commits/master)
  to find out if the bug was already fixed in the master branch.
- [x] I have included all related issues and possible duplicate issues in this issue
      (If there are none, check this box anyway).

## Related Issues and Possible Duplicates
<!--
Please make sure to search and mention any related issues
or possible duplicates to this issue as requested by the checklist above.

This may or may not include issues in other repositories that the Celery project
maintains or other repositories that are dependencies of Celery.

If you don't know how to mention issues, please refer to Github's documentation
on the subject: https://help.github.com/en/articles/autolinked-references-and-urls#issues-and-pull-requests
-->

#### Related Issues

- None

#### Possible Duplicates

- None

# Description
<!--
Please describe what's missing or incorrect about our documentation.
Include links and/or screenshots which will aid us to resolve the issue.
-->

In Tasks -> Instantiation, the following code snippet is used:

```
from celery import Task

class DatabaseTask(Task):
    _db = None

    @property
    def db(self):
        if self._db is None:
            self._db = Database.connect()
        return self._db

@app.task(base=DatabaseTask)
def process_rows():
    for row in process_rows.db.table.all():
        process_row(row)
```

By not using `bind=True`, `process_rows.db` will be None in other class methods such as `after_return`.

For example, this will fail:

```
from celery import Task

class DatabaseTask(Task):
    _db = None

    @property
    def db(self):
        if self._db is None:
            self._db = Database.connect()
        return self._db

    def after_return(self, status, retval, task_id, args, kwargs, einfo):
        if self._db is None:
            return
        self._db.close()
        # ^^^^ `self._db` is None

@app.task(base=DatabaseTask)
def process_rows():
    for row in process_rows.db.table.all():
        process_row(row)
```

# Suggestions
<!-- Please provide us suggestions for how to fix the documentation -->

Use `bind=True`.

issue.title: Enable tasks to be consumed without impacting the rate limit
issue.body:
- [x] I have checked the [issues list](https://github.com/celery/celery/issues?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=is%3Aissue+label%3A%22Issue+Type%3A+Feature+Request%22+)
  for similar or identical feature requests.
- [x] I have checked the [pull requests list](https://github.com/celery/celery/pulls?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=is%3Apr+label%3A%22PR+Type%3A+Feature%22+)
  for existing proposed implementations of this feature.
- [x] I have checked the [commit log](https://github.com/celery/celery/commits/master)
  to find out if the same feature was already implemented in the
  master branch.
- [x] I have included all related issues and possible duplicate issues
  in this issue (If there are none, check this box anyway).

# Brief Summary

In some situations you may want to handle cancellations without impacting rate limiting. For example:

```python
@shared_task(rate_limit="1/s")
def do_something_expensive(task_data):
  if is_cancelled(task_data):  # could check the expected task time, or the database, or anything
    return
  # expensive stuff
```

With the current rate limiting implementation, if you have 10,000 tasks in the queue and `is_cancelled` returns `True` for the first 5,000 of them, it will take ~1.3 hours for them to be processed with the `1/s` rate limit.

A way around this is to allow a task to signal that the task has been skipped and _not_ impact the rate limit, processing the next message immediately.

One way to do this could be to add a new exception type to signal this:

```python
@shared_task(rate_limit="1/s")
def do_something_expensive(task_data):
  if is_cancelled(task_data):
    raise TaskHasBeenSkippedDontCountThisAgainstTheRateLimit()
  # expensive stuff
```

If Celery is able to detect this exception is raised it can immediately pull the next message from the queue, ignoring the rate limit.

issue.title: SQS transport calls get_queue_url *every* time before receive_message - should cache?
issue.body:
When using the SQS transport (in my case with celery) I see a *lot* of `GetQueueUrl` AWS API calls (~900 per hour) which seems unnecessary given the queue URL essentially never changes.

As far as I can see this is because:
 - `kombu.transport.SQS.Channel._get_bulk_async` -> `_get_async` -> calls `_get_from_sqs`...
 - ...and `_get_from_sqs` does `queue_url = connection.get_queue_url(queue)` (if you you haven't specified `self.predefined_queues`)

Could `_get_from_sqs` check `self._queue_cache[queue]` instead to save re-fetching the queue URL every time?

There seems to be precedent for this e.g:
 - both `Channel._get_bulk` and `Channel._size` call `_new_queue`...
 - ...which checks `_queue_cache` regardless of whether `self.predefined_queues` exists or not

If the lack of caching is deliberate in this specific case, why is it different from the other cases where `_queue_cache` is used?

I realise that this could be avoided by putting the URLs in `predefined_queues`, but in our environment there are a lot of instances of the application and this extra faff when the discovery from `queue_name_prefix` combined with the queue name works excellently.

issue.title: Celery not configuring flower subcommand for user-defined preload CLI options
issue.body:
Per the [documentation][1], users may add a command-line option that is passed to all sub-commands by adding a Click Option instance to `user_options['preload']`. 

With this option, I've been able to pass an `--ini` cli option to the celery cli and configure my celery app from an ini file containing my application config.

However, because this new option is also passed to all sub-commands, `flower` fails to start as it does not recognize the new argument. Since new user-added options appear to work for other sub-commands like worker, beat, and events, I'm wondering if this is a bug in that celery is not passing this new command option down to flower?

This works for the `worker`, `beat` and `events` subcommands:

    $ celery -A example worker --ini app.ini
    app.ini

But it fails for the `flower` subcommand:

    $ celery -A example flower --ini app.ini

The traceback:

    Traceback (most recent call last):
      File "/usr/local/bin/celery", line 8, in <module>
        sys.exit(main())
      File "/usr/local/lib/python3.8/dist-packages/celery/__main__.py", line 15, in main
        sys.exit(_main())
      File "/usr/local/lib/python3.8/dist-packages/celery/bin/celery.py", line 217, in main
        return celery(auto_envvar_prefix="CELERY")
      File "/usr/local/lib/python3.8/dist-packages/click/core.py", line 1130, in __call__
        return self.main(*args, **kwargs)
      File "/usr/local/lib/python3.8/dist-packages/click/core.py", line 1055, in main
        rv = self.invoke(ctx)
      File "/usr/local/lib/python3.8/dist-packages/click/core.py", line 1657, in invoke
        return _process_result(sub_ctx.command.invoke(sub_ctx))
      File "/usr/local/lib/python3.8/dist-packages/click/core.py", line 1404, in invoke
        return ctx.invoke(self.callback, **ctx.params)
      File "/usr/local/lib/python3.8/dist-packages/click/core.py", line 760, in invoke
        return __callback(*args, **kwargs)
      File "/usr/local/lib/python3.8/dist-packages/click/decorators.py", line 26, in new_func
        return f(get_current_context(), *args, **kwargs)
    TypeError: flower() got an unexpected keyword argument 'ini'


**dependencies:**
* celery==5.2.7
* flower==1.2.0


**example.py**

    from celery import Celery
    from celery import signals
    from click import Option
    
    app = Celery()
    
    ini_option = Option(('-i', '--ini'), help='ini file path to use.')
    
    app.user_options['preload'].add(ini_option)
    
    @signals.user_preload_options.connect
    def on_preload_parsed(options, **kwargs):
        print(options['ini'])
        exit(-1)


  [1]: https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/latest/userguide/extending.html#preload-options

celeryconfig.py ```python from kombu import Queue broker_url = "redis://password@localhost:6379" result_backend = "redis://:password@localhost:6379" imports = ("worker",) worker_concurrency = 1 worker_prefetch_multiplier = 1 task_routes = {'task*': {'queue': 'test'}} task_queues = [Queue("test")] ``` worker.pi ```python import logging import time from celery import Celery import celeryconfig app = Celery("test") app.config_from_object(celeryconfig) logger = logging.getLogger(__name__) @app.task(name="task1") def task1(): pass ``` main.py ```python import signal import subprocess import time import redis from worker import task1 if __name__ == '__main__': r = redis.Redis(host='localhost', port=6379, db=0, password="") while True: # You may need to edit the initial timeout, depending on how fast/slow your PC is timeout = 1.2439 # this value actual for my PC step = 0.00001 # we will increase timeout with such step to catch the error task_id = task1.delay().task_id while True: try: p = subprocess.Popen(["celery", "-A", "worker", "worker", "-l", "info", "-E"]) time.sleep(timeout) p.send_signal(signal.SIGINT) except (subprocess.TimeoutExpired, BrokenPipeError): pass print(timeout) # Checking if there are task still in our queue. We need to continue test, # if that's true if r.lrange("test", 0, 1): timeout += step else: break # Sometimes we may miss the timing, so if the task is processed, we start all over again is_task_processed = not r.get("celery-task-meta-" + task_id) if is_task_processed: break ```

# Expected Behavior The task will be fetched from the queue when a warm shutdown is received. Expected redis operations: ``` LPUSH test {"body": "W1tdLCB7fSwgeyJjYWxsYmFja3MiOiBudWxsLCAiZXJyYmFja3MiOiBudWxsLCAiY2hhaW4iOiBudWxsLCAiY2hvcmQiOiBudWxsfV0=", "content-encoding": "utf-8", "content-type": "application/json", "headers": {"lang": "py", "task": "task1", "id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "shadow": null, "eta": null, "expires": null, "group": null, "group_index": null, "retries": 0, "timelimit": [null, null], "root_id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "parent_id": null, "argsrepr": "()", "kwargsrepr": "{}", "origin": "gen13915@igor-pc-work", "ignore_result": false}, "properties": {"correlation_id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "reply_to": "36f586c8-1387-3a19-8eb3-12dbefcfaeb8", "delivery_mode": 2, "delivery_info": {"exchange": "", "routing_key": "test"}, "priority": 0, "body_encoding": "base64", "delivery_tag": "beeb3fc1-8524-4212-a14d-9bee5343f353"}} RPOP test MULTI ZADD unacked_index 1670591793.386102 beeb3fc1-8524-4212-a14d-9bee5343f353 HSET unacked beeb3fc1-8524-4212-a14d-9bee5343f353 [{"body": "W1tdLCB7fSwgeyJjYWxsYmFja3MiOiBudWxsLCAiZXJyYmFja3MiOiBudWxsLCAiY2hhaW4iOiBudWxsLCAiY2hvcmQiOiBudWxsfV0=", "content-encoding": "utf-8", "content-type": "application/json", "headers": {"lang": "py", "task": "task1", "id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "shadow": null, "eta": null, "expires": null, "group": null, "group_index": null, "retries": 0, "timelimit": [null, null], "root_id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "parent_id": null, "argsrepr": "()", "kwargsrepr": "{}", "origin": "gen13915@igor-pc-work", "ignore_result": false}, "properties": {"correlation_id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "reply_to": "36f586c8-1387-3a19-8eb3-12dbefcfaeb8", "delivery_mode": 2, "delivery_info": {"exchange": "", "routing_key": "test"}, "priority": 0, "body_encoding": "base64", "delivery_tag": "beeb3fc1-8524-4212-a14d-9bee5343f353"}}, "", "test"] EXEC ``` # Actual Behavior The task is removed from the custom queue and is not moved to the unacked queue When fetching a task from the queue, the worker calls the RPOP function in redis and moves the returned task to unacked. In my case, if you get to the right timing with the worker turned off, then the worker will only call RPOP in redis and then shutdown without transferring the task to unacked. Thus, the task will simply be deleted. Actual redis operations logs : ``` LPUSH test {"body": "W1tdLCB7fSwgeyJjYWxsYmFja3MiOiBudWxsLCAiZXJyYmFja3MiOiBudWxsLCAiY2hhaW4iOiBudWxsLCAiY2hvcmQiOiBudWxsfV0=", "content-encoding": "utf-8", "content-type": "application/json", "headers": {"lang": "py", "task": "task1", "id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "shadow": null, "eta": null, "expires": null, "group": null, "group_index": null, "retries": 0, "timelimit": [null, null], "root_id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "parent_id": null, "argsrepr": "()", "kwargsrepr": "{}", "origin": "gen13915@igor-pc-work", "ignore_result": false}, "properties": {"correlation_id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "reply_to": "36f586c8-1387-3a19-8eb3-12dbefcfaeb8", "delivery_mode": 2, "delivery_info": {"exchange": "", "routing_key": "test"}, "priority": 0, "body_encoding": "base64", "delivery_tag": "beeb3fc1-8524-4212-a14d-9bee5343f353"}} RPOP test ``` P.S. We have such a problem in a production using Kuber autoscaling in the Google cloud.

issue.title: Regard backend redis's switching to replica as recoverable error
issue.body:
<!--
Please fill this template entirely and do not erase parts of it.
We reserve the right to close without a response
enhancement requests which are incomplete.
-->
# Checklist
<!--
To check an item on the list replace [ ] with [x].
-->

- [x] I have checked the [issues list](https://github.com/celery/celery/issues?q=is%3Aissue+label%3A%22Issue+Type%3A+Enhancement%22+-label%3A%22Category%3A+Documentation%22)
  for similar or identical enhancement to an existing feature.
- [x] I have checked the [pull requests list](https://github.com/celery/celery/pulls?q=is%3Apr+label%3A%22Issue+Type%3A+Enhancement%22+-label%3A%22Category%3A+Documentation%22)
  for existing proposed enhancements.
- [x] I have checked the [commit log](https://github.com/celery/celery/commits/master)
  to find out if the if the same enhancement was already implemented in the
  master branch.
- [x] I have included all related issues and possible duplicate issues in this issue
      (If there are none, check this box anyway).

## Related Issues and Possible Duplicates
<!--
Please make sure to search and mention any related issues
or possible duplicates to this issue as requested by the checklist above.

This may or may not include issues in other repositories that the Celery project
maintains or other repositories that are dependencies of Celery.

If you don't know how to mention issues, please refer to Github's documentation
on the subject: https://help.github.com/en/articles/autolinked-references-and-urls#issues-and-pull-requests
-->

#### Related Issues

- https://github.com/celery/celery/issues/6348
  - The situation is similar, but this issue is based on Redis Sentinel and we use AWS ElastiCache. Error message is also a bit different.

#### Possible Duplicates

- None

# Brief Summary
<!--
Please include a brief summary of what the enhancement is
and why it is needed.
-->

When AWS ElastiCache for Redis has a replication structure and causes a failover, Celery doesn't failover and the main process tries graceful shutdown. It means,
- main process exits due to Unrecoverable error when there is no remaining task
- main process hangs until the remaining task finishes

The second one is critical for us because we have many long ongoing tasks. The first one is better than it because we automatically reboot the process, but we'd like to avoid it because Redis failover is a kind of expected behavior.

If some change is acceptable, we will try to create a pull request by ourselves.

# Detail

We got the following error when ElastiCache failover happened.
```
[CRITICAL - 2022-11-04 10:45:27 - 21 worker:207] Unrecoverable error: ReadOnlyError("You can't write against a read only replica.")
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/celery/worker/worker.py", line 203, in start
    self.blueprint.start(self)
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/celery/bootsteps.py", line 116, in start
    step.start(parent)
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/celery/bootsteps.py", line 365, in start
    return self.obj.start()
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/celery/worker/consumer/consumer.py", line 326, in start
    blueprint.start(self)
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/celery/bootsteps.py", line 116, in start
    step.start(parent)
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/celery/worker/consumer/consumer.py", line 618, in start
    c.loop(*c.loop_args())
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/celery/worker/loops.py", line 97, in asynloop
    next(loop)
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/kombu/asynchronous/hub.py", line 362, in create_loop
    cb(*cbargs)
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/kombu/transport/redis.py", line 1266, in on_readable
    self.cycle.on_readable(fileno)
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/kombu/transport/redis.py", line 504, in on_readable
    chan.handlers[type]()
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/kombu/transport/redis.py", line 898, in _brpop_read
    **options)
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/redis/client.py", line 1189, in parse_response
    response = connection.read_response()
  File "/var/www/venv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/redis/connection.py", line 817, in read_response
    raise response
redis.exceptions.ReadOnlyError: You can't write against a read only replica.
```

As far as we checked, an error during connection becomes `ConnectionError` and regarded as "Recoverable", but `ReadOnlyError` (and its parent `ResponseError`) is regarded as "Unrecoverable".

# Design

## Architectural Considerations
<!--
If more components other than Celery are involved,
describe them here and the effect it would have on Celery.
-->
Maybe this part in kombu is related
https://github.com/celery/kombu/blob/v5.2.3/kombu/transport/redis.py#L128-L141

## Proposed Behavior
<!--
Please describe in detail how this enhancement is going to change the behavior
of an existing feature.
Describe what happens in case of failures as well if applicable.
-->
When an error happens due to switching master to replica, retry connection and connect to the new master.

## Proposed UI/UX
<!--
Please provide your ideas for the API, CLI options,
configuration key names etc. that will be adjusted for this enhancement.
-->
- Adding some option to regard ResponseError as "Recoverable".  Configuration key like `redis_retry_on_response_error` or `redis_retry_on_failover`?

But we're not sure if regarding ResponseError as "Recoverable" has a critical impact on existing behavior. We'd really appreciate advice from the community.

## Diagrams
<!--
Please include any diagrams that might be relevant
to the implementation of this enhancement such as:
* Class Diagrams
* Sequence Diagrams
* Activity Diagrams
You can drag and drop images into the text box to attach them to this issue.
-->
N/A

## Alternatives
<!--
If you have considered any alternative implementations
describe them in detail below.
-->
None

issue.title: ignore_result in task-decorator is ignored
issue.body:
Occurring in celery 5.2.7

When using celery with redis result-backend, passing `ignore_result` to the task decorator has no influence on the task result being stored.

```python3
@celery.task(ingore_result=True)
def task_2(*args, **kwargs):
    return "t2 return"

# these calls will create a celery-task-meta-<task_id> key in the corresponding redis result-backend
task_2.apply_async(ignore_result=False)
task_2.apply_async()
# this call will not store anything in the result backend
task_2.apply_async(ignore_result=True)
```

According to the [docs](https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/latest/userguide/tasks.html#ignore-results-you-don-t-want) the option precedence order is:

1.  Global [task_ignore_result](https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/latest/userguide/configuration.html#std-setting-task_ignore_result)
2.  [ignore_result](https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/latest/reference/celery.app.task.html#celery.app.task.Task.ignore_result) option
3.  Task execution option ignore_result

So i would expect `task_2.apply_async()` to ignore its result.

issue.title: Pulling the rug out from under FOSS users
issue.body:
I've used Rainbow Brackets for ages. The initial release was way good enough - just the paired-brackets support was great.

Since then, there's been a bunch of features added - of which I use none. However, I see now a change such that I need to pay for these features that I don't want - the plugin remains disabled unless I select to either pay, or go on a trial license, because I'm writing code in C#.

I understand the desire to make money off of your own software - and it's _your_ software to choose with what _you_ want to do - but I feel like the rug was pulled out from under existing users. The licensing info says that the free features remain free, but suddenly, C# isn't free. It's quite disappointing. The price, being in dollars, isn't (imo) a fair trade; neither is a recurring payment system for a user who has never, ever needed support - as I say, the initial offering was exactly what I was looking for.

issue.title: User Agents outdated
issue.body:
<!-- 🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅
Hi there! 😄

To expedite issue processing please search open and closed issues before submitting a new one. Existing issues often contain information about workarounds, resolution, or progress updates.
🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅🔅 -->

# 🐞 bug report

### ✍️ Description

We use [browserslist-useragent-regexp](https://github.com/browserslist/browserslist-useragent-regexp) to check that our users are not using older browsers.
But your User Agents are outdated, especially for Iphone devices.
For example you define this: `Mozilla/5.0 (iPhone; CPU iPhone OS 13_2_3 like Mac OS X) AppleWebKit/605.1.15 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/13.0.3 Mobile/15E148 Safari/604.1` for the Iphone 12 Pro. However iOS 13 was released in September 2019. On iPhone, browsers are updated with the OS, so we consider this browser to be obsolete.
You should change `iPhone OS 13_2_3` to `iPhone OS 16_1`
This problem occurs on many User Agents, even desktop ones.

It seems to be the same issue as here [703](https://github.com/responsively-org/responsively-app/issues/703)

### 🔧 Hypothetical solutions

I see two solutions, either regularly update the hardcoded values or allow editing of the preconfigured devices.

### 🕵🏼‍♂️ Is this a regression?

No.

### 🔬 Minimal Reproduction

Just follow the 4 steps from [browserslist-useragent-regexp](https://github.com/browserslist/browserslist-useragent-regexp#browserslist-useragent-regexp)

You can test our [website](https://demo-sitecarriere-classique.cvcatcher.io/) in the app, and you will be redirected to the "unsupported browsers" page.

### 🔥 Screenshot

![Demo-sitecarriere-classique - Full - iPhone 12-13 Pro - 2022-12-01 at 11 07 43 AM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/38187278/205025812-19dbc65e-ab80-4fe7-8189-fc8fdc252b09.jpg)

issue.title: About task_acks_late
issue.body:
Hi all,
         After i  read the doc about the [task_acks_late](https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/stable/glossary.html#term-late-acknowledgment),  i do the test but found something not the same as description, my procedure was the following:

First start the celery worker in one shell and it will consume the default queue task
```
celery -A celery_ini worker -l info
```

Celery App configure like this:
```
from celery import Celery
app = Celery('tasks1', broker="redis://:xxxxx@xxxxx:xxxxx/0",
             backend="mongodb://xxxxx:xxxxx@xxxxx:xxxxx/xxxxx?authSource=xxxxx&maxPoolSize=xxxxx&replicaSet=xxxxx",
             include=["tasks"])
app.conf.update(
    worker_concurrency=2,
    worker_prefetch_multiplier=2,
    task_acks_late=True
)
```

Add task code like this:
```
@app.task
  def add(x, y):
      import time
      time.sleep(30)
      print(f"x+y={x+y}")
      return x + y
```

and i call the task in another shell 
```
from tasks import add
from celery import group
all_tasks=group(add.s(1,i) for i in range(6))
all_tasks.delay()
```

Now ,if as the prefork thread was doing the first 2 job we kill the worker use this cmd 
```
for i in `ps -ef | grep celery | grep -v grep | grep -v flower | awk '{print $2}'`;do kill -9 $i;done;
```   
 
i lost the **exec task** and **reserved task** , the broker was only have **2** task,

but the doc say this， 

> late acknowledgment
Task is [acknowledged](https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/stable/glossary.html#term-acknowledged) after execution (both if successful, or if the task is raising an error), which means the task will be redelivered to another worker in the event of the machine losing power, or the worker instance being killed mid-execution.

so was i misunderstanding this ? can anyone help me ?

issue.title: Statistics of Workers: Add information of idle state
issue.body:
# Checklist

- [x] I have checked the [issues list](https://github.com/celery/celery/issues?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=is%3Aissue+label%3A%22Issue+Type%3A+Feature+Request%22+)
  for similar or identical feature requests.
- [x] I have checked the [pull requests list](https://github.com/celery/celery/pulls?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=is%3Apr+label%3A%22PR+Type%3A+Feature%22+)
  for existing proposed implementations of this feature.
- [x] I have checked the [commit log](https://github.com/celery/celery/commits/master)
  to find out if the same feature was already implemented in the
  master branch.
- [x] I have included all related issues and possible duplicate issues
  in this issue (If there are none, check this box anyway).

## Related Issues and Possible Duplicates
- None

#### Related Issues

- None

#### Possible Duplicates

- None

# Brief Summary
I'd like to determine if a worker is idle (no new tasks available and non currently executed) and how long it is already in this state.

I'm running celery workers in a self-scaling environment.
Depending on this idle-state I'd like to automatically scale the amount of workers up or down by an external "auto-scaler".

This could be done by increase/decrease the `replicas` spec of the parent `Deployment`, adjusting `minReplicas` of an `HorizontalPodAutoscaler` of K8s or to start/stop pods using the K8s API.
For docker-compose one can use the `--scale` parameter etc - just to name a few possibilities.

[The scaling algorithm I'd like to implement is something like GitLab is using](https://docs.gitlab.com/runner/configuration/autoscale.html#autoscaling-algorithm-and-parameters).
It works by checking how many workers are idle (and how long) which results in scaling down if it exceeds a certain treshold or if all of them are busy, scaling up so that anytime X workers are free (and thus idle) to pick new tasks.

Celery provides `control.inspect().active()` which outputs the current running tasks per worker.
However, on very short-running tasks and `concurrent=1` and `prefetch=0` this nearly always returns an empty list.
Independent if this is a "good" celery configuration, because of this, it would not be a applicable way of getting the current state of a worker.

Celery provides a `control.inspect().stats()` command.
It includes a `total` dictionary with task names as keys and the amount of tasks executed by the worker as values.
One could sum up those values and keep track if they increase to determine if the worker "is still working".

# Design

## Architectural Considerations
None

## Proposed Behavior
Add additional information to the `stats()` command for each worker to determine how long a worker is idle.
That could be done by adding `idle` as an additional return value which consists of `int` seconds since the worker worked on a task.
For long running tasks this value stays at `0`.

External scripts could check this value to determine if a worker is idle - at least in Python it would automatically evaluate to `false` if `0` and is otherwise `true`.
Also it gives the developer the freedom to decide to wait until `idle` exceeds a given threshold before any action is taken.

## Proposed UI/UX
N/A _API/CLI only_

## Diagrams
N/A

## Alternatives
None (see summary)

## Expected Behavior

issue.title: Disabling 'Semantic highlighting' should disable rainbow variables
issue.body:
## Expected Behavior
Disabling the default `Semantic highlighting` option should also disable the plugin `Enable rainbow variable` option.

## Current Behavior
Disabling the default `Semantic highlighting`  works for the current project, but the option gets activated back when you open a new project/restart the editor.

---

Got a notification suggesting to use rainbow variables, wanted to try it but didn't understood it was coming from this plugin because I had to activate an option in the default editor settings.
Didn't liked the way it looked so I tried to disabled it, but couldn't figure out why the editor couldn't keep the setting disabled.

Don't know if there is a good fix for that but other people might have the same issue.

Thx for the great work on the plugin !

issue.body:

  to find out if the same feature was already implemented in the
  master branch.
- [x] I have included all related issues and possible duplicate issues
  in this issue (If there are none, check this box anyway).

## Related Issues and Possible Duplicates
<!--
Please make sure to search and mention any related issues
or possible duplicates to this issue as requested by the checklist above.

This may or may not include issues in other repositories that the Celery project
maintains or other repositories that are dependencies of Celery.

If you don't know how to mention issues, please refer to Github's documentation
on the subject: https://help.github.com/en/articles/autolinked-references-and-urls#issues-and-pull-requests
-->

#### Related Issues

- [Kombu 279](https://github.com/celery/kombu/issues/279)

#### Possible Duplicates

- None

# Brief Summary
<!--
Please include a brief summary of what the feature does
and why it is needed.
-->
Some brokers, in our case SQS, do not support large tasks (>256KB). Rather than send the task data through the broker, one may want to save the task data to the result backend, in our case specifically Redis, and only send an ID for that data through the broker allowing larger tasks to support more brokers.

There is an [issue](https://github.com/celery/kombu/issues/279) for kombu that seeks to fix the size limit for but if a result_backend is present, wouldn't it be better to save the task to that, and then load it when it's needed? While https://github.com/celery/kombu/issues/279 fixes SQS, it won't fix RabbitMQ's 512MB max limit, which we have also hit on some occasions. In cases when using a broker with a heavily limited size cap, like SQS, or when generating and sending incredibley large tasks, only sending a result_id referencing the result data stored in the backend would be helpful.

# Design

## Architectural Considerations
<!--
If more components other than Celery are involved,
describe them here and the effect it would have on Celery.
-->
None

## Proposed Behavior
<!--
Please describe in detail how this feature is going to behave.
Describe what happens in case of failures as well if applicable.
-->
* In the trace module https://github.com/celery/celery/blob/master/celery/app/trace.py#L448 before executing the celery task, the `result_backend_data` should be restored using the id in that dict, this key should be present in the kwargs 
* apply_async calls in https://github.com/celery/celery/blob/master/celery/app/trace.py#L479-L504 should be modified to only the id using result_backend_data, and not the actual result data

issue.body:
<!--
Please fill this template entirely and do not erase parts of it.
We reserve the right to close without a response
bug reports which are incomplete.
-->
# Checklist
<!--
To check an item on the list replace [ ] with [x].
-->

- [x] I have checked the [issues list](https://github.com/celery/celery/issues?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=is%3Aissue+label%3A%22Category%3A+Documentation%22+)
  for similar or identical bug reports.
- [x] I have checked the [pull requests list](https://github.com/celery/celery/pulls?q=is%3Apr+label%3A%22Category%3A+Documentation%22)
  for existing proposed fixes.
- [x] I have checked the [commit log](https://github.com/celery/celery/commits/master)
  to find out if the bug was already fixed in the master branch.
- [x] I have included all related issues and possible duplicate issues in this issue
      (If there are none, check this box anyway).

## Related Issues and Possible Duplicates
<!--
Please make sure to search and mention any related issues
or possible duplicates to this issue as requested by the checklist above.

This may or may not include issues in other repositories that the Celery project
maintains or other repositories that are dependencies of Celery.

If you don't know how to mention issues, please refer to Github's documentation
on the subject: https://help.github.com/en/articles/autolinked-references-and-urls#issues-and-pull-requests
-->

#### Related Issues

- None

#### Possible Duplicates

- None

# Description
<!--
Please describe what's missing or incorrect about our documentation.
Include links and/or screenshots which will aid us to resolve the issue.
-->

In Tasks -> Instantiation, the following code snippet is used:

```
from celery import Task

class DatabaseTask(Task):
    _db = None

    @property
    def db(self):
        if self._db is None:
            self._db = Database.connect()
        return self._db

@app.task(base=DatabaseTask)
def process_rows():
    for row in process_rows.db.table.all():
        process_row(row)
```

By not using `bind=True`, `process_rows.db` will be None in other class methods such as `after_return`.

For example, this will fail:

```
from celery import Task

class DatabaseTask(Task):
    _db = None

    @property
    def db(self):
        if self._db is None:
            self._db = Database.connect()
        return self._db

    def after_return(self, status, retval, task_id, args, kwargs, einfo):
        if self._db is None:
            return
        self._db.close()
        # ^^^^ `self._db` is None

@app.task(base=DatabaseTask)
def process_rows():
    for row in process_rows.db.table.all():
        process_row(row)
```

# Suggestions
<!-- Please provide us suggestions for how to fix the documentation -->

Use `bind=True`.

issue.title: Loading browser data

I have a vuejs app that uses vuex to store data I load into my add from files and endpoints. When I load this data in the screen in Responsively in which I load the data works as expected but the other screen are not kept in sync. 

Is there a setting in the app I need to adjust or is this a corner case that has not yet been worked?

I use Python, C# and C/C++

It should give a license for studnets, and the licenses windows should say "activated" in the extension.

issue.title: Enable tasks to be consumed without impacting the rate limit
issue.body:
- [x] I have checked the [issues list](https://github.com/celery/celery/issues?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=is%3Aissue+label%3A%22Issue+Type%3A+Feature+Request%22+)
  for similar or identical feature requests.
- [x] I have checked the [pull requests list](https://github.com/celery/celery/pulls?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=is%3Apr+label%3A%22PR+Type%3A+Feature%22+)
  for existing proposed implementations of this feature.
- [x] I have checked the [commit log](https://github.com/celery/celery/commits/master)
  to find out if the same feature was already implemented in the
  master branch.
- [x] I have included all related issues and possible duplicate issues
  in this issue (If there are none, check this box anyway).

# Brief Summary

In some situations you may want to handle cancellations without impacting rate limiting. For example:

```python
@shared_task(rate_limit="1/s")
def do_something_expensive(task_data):
  if is_cancelled(task_data):  # could check the expected task time, or the database, or anything
    return
  # expensive stuff
```

With the current rate limiting implementation, if you have 10,000 tasks in the queue and `is_cancelled` returns `True` for the first 5,000 of them, it will take ~1.3 hours for them to be processed with the `1/s` rate limit.

A way around this is to allow a task to signal that the task has been skipped and _not_ impact the rate limit, processing the next message immediately.

One way to do this could be to add a new exception type to signal this:

```python
@shared_task(rate_limit="1/s")
def do_something_expensive(task_data):
  if is_cancelled(task_data):
    raise TaskHasBeenSkippedDontCountThisAgainstTheRateLimit()
  # expensive stuff
```

If Celery is able to detect this exception is raised it can immediately pull the next message from the queue, ignoring the rate limit.

issue.title: SQS transport calls get_queue_url *every* time before receive_message - should cache?
issue.body:
When using the SQS transport (in my case with celery) I see a *lot* of `GetQueueUrl` AWS API calls (~900 per hour) which seems unnecessary given the queue URL essentially never changes.

As far as I can see this is because:
 - `kombu.transport.SQS.Channel._get_bulk_async` -> `_get_async` -> calls `_get_from_sqs`...
 - ...and `_get_from_sqs` does `queue_url = connection.get_queue_url(queue)` (if you you haven't specified `self.predefined_queues`)

Could `_get_from_sqs` check `self._queue_cache[queue]` instead to save re-fetching the queue URL every time?

There seems to be precedent for this e.g:
 - both `Channel._get_bulk` and `Channel._size` call `_new_queue`...
 - ...which checks `_queue_cache` regardless of whether `self.predefined_queues` exists or not

If the lack of caching is deliberate in this specific case, why is it different from the other cases where `_queue_cache` is used?

I realise that this could be avoided by putting the URLs in `predefined_queues`, but in our environment there are a lot of instances of the application and this extra faff when the discovery from `queue_name_prefix` combined with the queue name works excellently.

issue.title: Celery not configuring flower subcommand for user-defined preload CLI options
issue.body:
Per the [documentation][1], users may add a command-line option that is passed to all sub-commands by adding a Click Option instance to `user_options['preload']`. 

With this option, I've been able to pass an `--ini` cli option to the celery cli and configure my celery app from an ini file containing my application config.

However, because this new option is also passed to all sub-commands, `flower` fails to start as it does not recognize the new argument. Since new user-added options appear to work for other sub-commands like worker, beat, and events, I'm wondering if this is a bug in that celery is not passing this new command option down to flower?

This works for the `worker`, `beat` and `events` subcommands:

    $ celery -A example worker --ini app.ini
    app.ini

But it fails for the `flower` subcommand:

    $ celery -A example flower --ini app.ini

The traceback:

    Traceback (most recent call last):
      File "/usr/local/bin/celery", line 8, in <module>
        sys.exit(main())
      File "/usr/local/lib/python3.8/dist-packages/celery/__main__.py", line 15, in main
        sys.exit(_main())
      File "/usr/local/lib/python3.8/dist-packages/celery/bin/celery.py", line 217, in main
        return celery(auto_envvar_prefix="CELERY")
      File "/usr/local/lib/python3.8/dist-packages/click/core.py", line 1130, in __call__
        return self.main(*args, **kwargs)
      File "/usr/local/lib/python3.8/dist-packages/click/core.py", line 1055, in main
        rv = self.invoke(ctx)
      File "/usr/local/lib/python3.8/dist-packages/click/core.py", line 1657, in invoke
        return _process_result(sub_ctx.command.invoke(sub_ctx))
      File "/usr/local/lib/python3.8/dist-packages/click/core.py", line 1404, in invoke
        return ctx.invoke(self.callback, **ctx.params)
      File "/usr/local/lib/python3.8/dist-packages/click/core.py", line 760, in invoke
        return __callback(*args, **kwargs)
      File "/usr/local/lib/python3.8/dist-packages/click/decorators.py", line 26, in new_func
        return f(get_current_context(), *args, **kwargs)
    TypeError: flower() got an unexpected keyword argument 'ini'


**dependencies:**
* celery==5.2.7
* flower==1.2.0


**example.py**

    from celery import Celery
    from celery import signals
    from click import Option
    
    app = Celery()
    
    ini_option = Option(('-i', '--ini'), help='ini file path to use.')
    
    app.user_options['preload'].add(ini_option)
    
    @signals.user_preload_options.connect
    def on_preload_parsed(options, **kwargs):
        print(options['ini'])
        exit(-1)


  [1]: https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/latest/userguide/extending.html#preload-options

issue.title: Celery worker deletes task from MQ during fetching after shutdown
issue.body:
# Checklist - [x] I have verified that the issue exists against the `master` branch of Celery. - [ ] This has already been asked to the [discussions forum](https://github.com/celery/celery/discussions) first. - [x] I have read the relevant section in the [contribution guide](https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/master/contributing.html#other-bugs) on reporting bugs. - [x] I have checked the [issues list](https://github.com/celery/celery/issues?q=is%3Aissue+label%3A%22Issue+Type%3A+Bug+Report%22+-label%3A%22Category%3A+Documentation%22) for similar or identical bug reports. - [x] I have checked the [pull requests list](https://github.com/celery/celery/pulls?q=is%3Apr+label%3A%22PR+Type%3A+Bugfix%22+-label%3A%22Category%3A+Documentation%22) for existing proposed fixes. - [x] I have checked the [commit log](https://github.com/celery/celery/commits/master) to find out if the bug was already fixed in the master branch. - [x] I have included all related issues and possible duplicate issues in this issue (If there are none, check this box anyway). ## Mandatory Debugging Information - [x] I have included the output of ``celery -A proj report`` in the issue. (if you are not able to do this, then at least specify the Celery version affected). - [x] I have verified that the issue exists against the `master` branch of Celery. - [x] I have included the contents of ``pip freeze`` in the issue. - [x] I have included all the versions of all the external dependencies required to reproduce this bug. ## Optional Debugging Information - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one Python version and/or implementation. - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one message broker and/or result backend. - [x] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one version of the message broker and/or result backend. - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one operating system. - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one workers pool. - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue with autoscaling, retries, ETA/Countdown & rate limits disabled. - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue after downgrading and/or upgrading Celery and its dependencies. ## Related Issues and Possible Duplicates #### Related Issues - None #### Possible Duplicates - None ## Environment & Settings **Celery version**: 5.2.7 and 4.3.0
celery report Output:

``` software -> celery:5.2.7 (dawn-chorus) kombu:5.2.4 py:3.8.0 billiard:3.6.4.0 redis:4.4.0 platform -> system:Linux arch:64bit, ELF kernel version:5.15.0-56-generic imp:CPython loader -> celery.loaders.app.AppLoader settings -> transport:redis results:redis://:**@localhost:6379/ Queue: broker_url: 'redis://:********@localhost:6379//' imports: ('worker',) logging: result_backend: 'redis://:********@localhost:6379/' task_queues: [ -> >] task_routes: { 'task*': {'queue': 'test'}} worker_concurrency: 1 worker_prefetch_multiplier: 1 deprecated_settings: None ```

# Steps to Reproduce ## Required Dependencies * **Minimal Python Version**: 3.8 * **Minimal Celery Version**: 4.3.0 * **Minimal Kombu Version**: 4.6.11 * **Minimal Broker Version**: 7.0 * **Minimal Result Backend Version**: 7.0 * **Minimal OS and/or Kernel Version**: Ubuntu 22.04 and kernel version:5.15.0-56-generic * **Minimal Broker Client Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Result Backend Client Version**: N/A or Unknown ### Python Packages
pip freeze Output:

``` amqp==5.1.1 async-timeout==4.0.2 billiard==3.6.4.0 celery==5.2.7 click==8.1.3 click-didyoumean==0.3.0 click-plugins==1.1.1 click-repl==0.2.0 kombu==5.2.4 prompt-toolkit==3.0.36 psutil==5.9.4 pytz==2022.6 redis==4.4.0 six==1.16.0 vine==5.0.0 wcwidth==0.2.5 ```

### Other Dependencies

N/A

## Minimally Reproducible Test Case

celeryconfig.py ```python from kombu import Queue broker_url = "redis://password@localhost:6379" result_backend = "redis://:password@localhost:6379" imports = ("worker",) worker_concurrency = 1 worker_prefetch_multiplier = 1 task_routes = {'task*': {'queue': 'test'}} task_queues = [Queue("test")] ``` worker.pi ```python import logging import time from celery import Celery import celeryconfig app = Celery("test") app.config_from_object(celeryconfig) logger = logging.getLogger(__name__) @app.task(name="task1") def task1(): pass ``` main.py ```python import signal import subprocess import time import redis from worker import task1 if __name__ == '__main__': r = redis.Redis(host='localhost', port=6379, db=0, password="") while True: # You may need to edit the initial timeout, depending on how fast/slow your PC is timeout = 1.2439 # this value actual for my PC step = 0.00001 # we will increase timeout with such step to catch the error task_id = task1.delay().task_id while True: try: p = subprocess.Popen(["celery", "-A", "worker", "worker", "-l", "info", "-E"]) time.sleep(timeout) p.send_signal(signal.SIGINT) except (subprocess.TimeoutExpired, BrokenPipeError): pass print(timeout) # Checking if there are task still in our queue. We need to continue test, # if that's true if r.lrange("test", 0, 1): timeout += step else: break # Sometimes we may miss the timing, so if the task is processed, we start all over again is_task_processed = not r.get("celery-task-meta-" + task_id) if is_task_processed: break ```

# Expected Behavior The task will be fetched from the queue when a warm shutdown is received. Expected redis operations: ``` LPUSH test {"body": "W1tdLCB7fSwgeyJjYWxsYmFja3MiOiBudWxsLCAiZXJyYmFja3MiOiBudWxsLCAiY2hhaW4iOiBudWxsLCAiY2hvcmQiOiBudWxsfV0=", "content-encoding": "utf-8", "content-type": "application/json", "headers": {"lang": "py", "task": "task1", "id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "shadow": null, "eta": null, "expires": null, "group": null, "group_index": null, "retries": 0, "timelimit": [null, null], "root_id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "parent_id": null, "argsrepr": "()", "kwargsrepr": "{}", "origin": "gen13915@igor-pc-work", "ignore_result": false}, "properties": {"correlation_id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "reply_to": "36f586c8-1387-3a19-8eb3-12dbefcfaeb8", "delivery_mode": 2, "delivery_info": {"exchange": "", "routing_key": "test"}, "priority": 0, "body_encoding": "base64", "delivery_tag": "beeb3fc1-8524-4212-a14d-9bee5343f353"}} RPOP test MULTI ZADD unacked_index 1670591793.386102 beeb3fc1-8524-4212-a14d-9bee5343f353 HSET unacked beeb3fc1-8524-4212-a14d-9bee5343f353 [{"body": "W1tdLCB7fSwgeyJjYWxsYmFja3MiOiBudWxsLCAiZXJyYmFja3MiOiBudWxsLCAiY2hhaW4iOiBudWxsLCAiY2hvcmQiOiBudWxsfV0=", "content-encoding": "utf-8", "content-type": "application/json", "headers": {"lang": "py", "task": "task1", "id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "shadow": null, "eta": null, "expires": null, "group": null, "group_index": null, "retries": 0, "timelimit": [null, null], "root_id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "parent_id": null, "argsrepr": "()", "kwargsrepr": "{}", "origin": "gen13915@igor-pc-work", "ignore_result": false}, "properties": {"correlation_id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "reply_to": "36f586c8-1387-3a19-8eb3-12dbefcfaeb8", "delivery_mode": 2, "delivery_info": {"exchange": "", "routing_key": "test"}, "priority": 0, "body_encoding": "base64", "delivery_tag": "beeb3fc1-8524-4212-a14d-9bee5343f353"}}, "", "test"] EXEC ``` # Actual Behavior The task is removed from the custom queue and is not moved to the unacked queue When fetching a task from the queue, the worker calls the RPOP function in redis and moves the returned task to unacked. In my case, if you get to the right timing with the worker turned off, then the worker will only call RPOP in redis and then shutdown without transferring the task to unacked. Thus, the task will simply be deleted. Actual redis operations logs : ``` LPUSH test {"body": "W1tdLCB7fSwgeyJjYWxsYmFja3MiOiBudWxsLCAiZXJyYmFja3MiOiBudWxsLCAiY2hhaW4iOiBudWxsLCAiY2hvcmQiOiBudWxsfV0=", "content-encoding": "utf-8", "content-type": "application/json", "headers": {"lang": "py", "task": "task1", "id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "shadow": null, "eta": null, "expires": null, "group": null, "group_index": null, "retries": 0, "timelimit": [null, null], "root_id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "parent_id": null, "argsrepr": "()", "kwargsrepr": "{}", "origin": "gen13915@igor-pc-work", "ignore_result": false}, "properties": {"correlation_id": "697a9736-46a6-4978-96cd-547a7b46f6ac", "reply_to": "36f586c8-1387-3a19-8eb3-12dbefcfaeb8", "delivery_mode": 2, "delivery_info": {"exchange": "", "routing_key": "test"}, "priority": 0, "body_encoding": "base64", "delivery_tag": "beeb3fc1-8524-4212-a14d-9bee5343f353"}} RPOP test ``` P.S. We have such a problem in a production using Kuber autoscaling in the Google cloud.
